{
  "Mechanical digestion in the mouth is called:": "",
  "Segmentation": "",
  "Mastication (chewing)": "",
  "Peristalsis": "",
  "Absorption": "",
  "Mastication is the process of chewing, in which the teeth physically break food into smaller pieces to increase surface area for enzymatic digestion.": "",
  "Chemical digestion of starch begins in the:": "",
  "Large intestine": "",
  "Stomach": "",
  "Small intestine": "",
  "Mouth (via salivary amylase)": "",
  "Salivary amylase, secreted by the salivary glands, begins the chemical breakdown of starch into maltose in the oral cavity, making the mouth the first site of carbohydrate digestion.": "",
  "Chief cells in the stomach produce:": "",
  "Intrinsic factor (for vitamin B12 absorption)": "",
  "Bile (for fat emulsification in the duodenum)": "",
  "Hydrochloric acid produced by parietal cells": "",
  "Pepsinogen (the inactive precursor of pepsin)": "",
  "Chief cells (also called peptic cells) secrete pepsinogen, which is converted to the active protease pepsin by hydrochloric acid in the gastric lumen.": "",
  "Parietal cells in the stomach produce:": "",
  "Bile salts": "",
  "Pepsinogen and gastric lipase": "",
  "Mucus and bicarbonate": "",
  "HCl and intrinsic factor": "",
  "Parietal cells secrete hydrochloric acid (which creates the acidic environment needed for pepsin activation and bacterial killing) and intrinsic factor (essential for vitamin B12 absorption in the ileum).": "",
  "Bile is produced by the _____ and stored in the _____.": "",
  "Gallbladder; liver": "",
  "Liver; gallbladder": "",
  "Stomach; duodenum": "",
  "Pancreas; stomach": "",
  "The liver continuously produces bile, which is then transported via the hepatic ducts to the gallbladder where it is stored and concentrated until fat enters the duodenum and triggers its release.": "",
  "Trypsin and chymotrypsin are pancreatic enzymes that digest:": "",
  "Proteins (they are proteases)": "",
  "Fats": "",
  "Carbohydrates": "",
  "Nucleic acids": "",
  "Trypsin and chymotrypsin are pancreatic proteases secreted in inactive forms (trypsinogen and chymotrypsinogen) that become activated in the duodenum to cleave proteins into smaller peptides.": "",
  "Pancreatic lipase digests fats into:": "",
  "Glucose and fructose": "",
  "Monoglycerides and fatty acids": "",
  "Nucleotides": "",
  "Amino acids": "",
  "Pancreatic lipase hydrolyzes triglycerides into monoglycerides and free fatty acids, which can then be absorbed by enterocytes in the small intestine.": "",
  "The pyloric sphincter controls the flow of chyme from the:": "",
  "Mouth to the pharynx": "",
  "Stomach to the duodenum": "",
  "Esophagus to the stomach": "",
  "Small intestine to the large intestine": "",
  "The pyloric sphincter is a ring of smooth muscle at the distal end of the stomach that regulates the rate of gastric emptying, releasing small amounts of chyme into the duodenum at a time.": "",
  "Nucleases are pancreatic enzymes that digest:": "",
  "Carbohydrates into monosaccharides": "",
  "Proteins into amino acids": "",
  "Fats into fatty acids": "",
  "Nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) into nucleotides": "",
  "Pancreatic nucleases (DNase and RNase) break down DNA and RNA from ingested cells into their component nucleotides, which are then further broken down and absorbed in the small intestine.": "",
  "Brush border enzymes (maltase, sucrase, lactase) are located in the:": "",
  "Salivary glands on the surface of lingual epithelial cells": "",
  "Small intestine on the microvilli of enterocytes": "",
  "Large intestine on the mucosal surface of colonocytes": "",
  "Stomach lining on the apical surface of gastric cells": "",
  "Brush border enzymes are membrane-bound enzymes on the microvilli of intestinal epithelial cells that complete the final stage of carbohydrate digestion by splitting disaccharides into absorbable monosaccharides.": "",
  "What is chyme?": "",
  "A digestive enzyme produced by the pancreas": "",
  "A semi-liquid mixture of partially digested food and gastric secretions produced in the stomach": "",
  "Solid, undigested food in the mouth": "",
  "Bile stored in the gallbladder": "",
  "Chyme is the thick, semi-liquid mass formed when food is mixed with hydrochloric acid and digestive enzymes in the stomach. It is gradually released through the pyloric sphincter into the duodenum for further digestion.": "",
  "What does emulsification mean in the context of fat digestion?": "",
  "The chemical breakdown of fat into fatty acids by enzymes": "",
  "The physical breaking of large fat globules into smaller droplets by bile salts to increase surface area for lipase": "",
  "The absorption of fat into lacteals": "",
  "The conversion of fat into glucose": "",
  "Emulsification is a mechanical process (not chemical digestion) in which bile salts act as detergents to break large fat globules into tiny droplets, dramatically increasing the surface area available for pancreatic lipase to act upon.": "",
  "What is segmentation?": "",
  "The voluntary chewing of food in the mouth": "",
  "Back-and-forth mixing contractions in the small intestine that blend chyme with digestive juices": "",
  "The churning motion unique to the stomach": "",
  "Wave-like contractions that push food forward through the GI tract": "",
  "Segmentation consists of localized, rhythmic contractions that divide and re-mix the chyme in the small intestine, maximizing contact with digestive enzymes and the absorptive surface without significantly propelling it forward.": "",
  "What does cholecystokinin (CCK) do?": "",
  "Inhibits all pancreatic secretion": "",
  "Stimulates gastric acid secretion in the stomach": "",
  "Triggers salivary amylase release": "",
  "Stimulates gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion in response to fat and protein in the duodenum": "",
  "CCK is a hormone released by I-cells in the duodenal mucosa when fats and proteins enter the small intestine. It stimulates the gallbladder to contract and release bile and the pancreas to secrete digestive enzymes.": "",
  "What is secretin?": "",
  "A bile salt produced by the liver": "",
  "A brush border enzyme on the microvilli": "",
  "A hormone released in response to acidic chyme in the duodenum that stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion": "",
  "An enzyme that digests proteins in the stomach": "",
  "Secretin is released by S-cells in the duodenum when acidic chyme arrives from the stomach. It stimulates the pancreas to secrete bicarbonate-rich fluid that neutralizes the acid, protecting the intestinal mucosa and creating an optimal pH for enzymes.": "",
  "What does gastrin do?": "",
  "Inhibits all digestive secretions": "",
  "Stimulates HCl secretion by parietal cells and increases gastric motility": "",
  "Neutralizes acid in the duodenum": "",
  "Causes the gallbladder to contract": "",
  "Gastrin is a hormone released by G-cells in the gastric antrum in response to food entering the stomach. It stimulates parietal cells to produce HCl and promotes gastric smooth muscle contractions to enhance churning.": "",
  "What does the term 'hydrolysis' mean in the context of digestion?": "",
  "The chemical splitting of bonds in macromolecules by the addition of water molecules": "",
  "The movement of food through the GI tract": "",
  "The absorption of water in the large intestine": "",
  "The physical breaking of food into smaller pieces": "",
  "Hydrolysis is the fundamental chemical reaction in digestion where enzymes use water to break covalent bonds in macromolecules (proteins, carbohydrates, fats, nucleic acids), splitting them into their smaller, absorbable subunits.": "",
  "What does lactose intolerance mean?": "",
  "A deficiency of the enzyme lactase that prevents the digestion of lactose (milk sugar), causing gas, bloating, and diarrhea": "",
  "An immune-mediated allergy to milk proteins": "",
  "An excess production of bile after consuming dairy": "",
  "An inability to absorb fat from dairy products": "",
  "Lactose intolerance occurs when there is insufficient lactase enzyme on the brush border of enterocytes, leaving undigested lactose in the intestinal lumen where it is fermented by bacteria, producing gas, bloating, cramping, and osmotic diarrhea.": "",
  "What is denaturation in the context of protein digestion?": "",
  "The synthesis of new proteins from amino acids": "",
  "The absorption of peptides across the intestinal wall": "",
  "The complete hydrolysis of proteins into individual amino acids": "",
  "The unfolding of a protein's three-dimensional structure by acid or heat, exposing peptide bonds to enzymatic attack": "",
  "Denaturation is a critical first step in protein digestion where the acidic environment of the stomach (pH 1.5-3.5) disrupts hydrogen bonds and other interactions that maintain a protein's shape, unfolding it so that proteases like pepsin can access and cleave internal peptide bonds.": "",
  "What is a bolus?": "",
  "A lipoprotein particle that transports fat in the lymph": "",
  "A wave of muscular contraction in the esophagus": "",
  "A soft, rounded mass of chewed food mixed with saliva that is swallowed from the mouth": "",
  "The semi-liquid mixture leaving the stomach": "",
  "A food bolus is formed during mastication when the tongue shapes chewed food mixed with saliva into a rounded mass suitable for swallowing. It travels through the pharynx and down the esophagus via peristalsis to the stomach.": "",
  "A patient reports that after drinking a glass of milk, she experiences severe bloating, gas, and watery diarrhea within 30 minutes. She has no skin rash or anaphylaxis. Which enzyme deficiency most likely explains her symptoms?": "",
  "Lactase deficiency": "",
  "Pepsin deficiency": "",
  "Pancreatic lipase deficiency": "",
  "Salivary amylase deficiency": "",
  "The symptoms of gas, bloating, and osmotic diarrhea after dairy consumption without allergic signs (rash, anaphylaxis) are classic for lactase deficiency (lactose intolerance), where undigested lactose is fermented by colonic bacteria.": "",
  "A 50-year-old man with chronic alcohol use presents with severe epigastric pain radiating to his back. Labs show serum lipase elevated to 5 times normal. The elevated lipase indicates damage to which organ?": "",
  "Liver": "",
  "Gallbladder": "",
  "Pancreas": "",
  "Elevated serum lipase is the most sensitive and specific marker for acute pancreatitis. Lipase is normally confined to the pancreas, and when pancreatic cells are damaged by inflammation (often from alcohol or gallstones), lipase leaks into the bloodstream.": "",
  "A patient taking proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) long-term notices she cannot absorb vitamin B12 well. Which cell type's function is being suppressed by the medication, and why does this affect B12 absorption?": "",
  "Goblet cells; less mucus means less B12 transport": "",
  "Chief cells; pepsinogen is needed to release B12 from food": "",
  "Parietal cells; reduced HCl impairs B12 release from food and reduced intrinsic factor impairs ileal B12 absorption": "",
  "G cells; less gastrin means less bile production": "",
  "PPIs suppress the proton pumps of parietal cells, reducing both HCl (needed to liberate B12 from food proteins) and intrinsic factor (required for B12 absorption in the ileum). Long-term PPI use can therefore lead to B12 deficiency.": "",
  "A medical student is reviewing a case where a patient had his gallbladder removed (cholecystectomy). The student wonders how this patient will digest fats. Which statement is correct?": "",
  "The patient will be completely unable to digest fats": "",
  "The stomach will compensate by increasing acid production": "",
  "The pancreas will take over bile production": "",
  "The liver still produces bile that drains directly into the duodenum, but the patient may have difficulty with large fatty meals": "",
  "After cholecystectomy, bile is still produced by the liver and flows continuously into the duodenum via the common bile duct. However, without the gallbladder to store and concentrate bile, the patient may experience difficulty digesting large amounts of fat at one time.": "",
  "An infant is found to have a genetic mutation that prevents activation of trypsinogen in the duodenum. This mutation most likely involves a deficiency of which enzyme?": "",
  "Salivary amylase": "",
  "Pepsin": "",
  "Enterokinase (enteropeptidase)": "",
  "Pancreatic lipase": "",
  "Enterokinase (enteropeptidase) is the brush border enzyme that converts trypsinogen to active trypsin in the duodenum. Since trypsin then activates the other pancreatic zymogens, a deficiency of enterokinase would impair the activation of the entire cascade of pancreatic proteases.": "",
  "A patient eats a meal rich in fat and protein. Within minutes, a hormone is released from the duodenum that causes the gallbladder to contract and the pancreas to secrete enzymes. Which hormone is responsible?": "",
  "Cholecystokinin (CCK)": "",
  "Gastrin": "",
  "Secretin": "",
  "Motilin": "",
  "CCK is released by I-cells in the duodenal and jejunal mucosa in response to the presence of fats and amino acids. It triggers gallbladder contraction to release bile and stimulates the acinar cells of the pancreas to secrete digestive enzymes.": "",
  "A nursing student notices that a tube-fed patient receiving formula directly into the jejunum is not digesting starch well. The student hypothesizes that the formula bypasses the action of which enzymes?": "",
  "Salivary amylase (oral) and any early duodenal contact with pancreatic amylase": "",
  "Brush border enzymes (maltase, sucrase)": "",
  "Trypsin and chymotrypsin": "",
  "Pepsin and gastric lipase only": "",
  "Jejunal tube feeding bypasses the mouth (where salivary amylase begins starch digestion) and the duodenum (where pancreatic amylase continues it). Though pancreatic amylase still reaches the jejunum, the lack of oral initiation may reduce overall starch digestion efficiency.": "",
  "A researcher studying a patient with Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (gastrin-secreting tumor) finds extremely high HCl levels in the stomach. Which of the following consequences would you expect?": "",
  "Decreased protein digestion because pepsinogen cannot be activated": "",
  "Increased carbohydrate digestion in the stomach": "",
  "Improved fat digestion from enhanced bile secretion": "",
  "Peptic ulcers in the stomach and duodenum due to excessive acid damaging the mucosal lining": "",
  "In Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, a gastrinoma produces excessive gastrin, leading to massive HCl oversecretion. This overwhelms the mucosal defense mechanisms and causes severe, often multiple peptic ulcers in the stomach and duodenum.": "",
  "A patient with cystic fibrosis has thick mucus blocking the pancreatic ducts, preventing digestive enzymes from reaching the duodenum. Which macronutrients will be most poorly digested?": "",
  "None, because the stomach can compensate for all pancreatic enzymes": "",
  "Only carbohydrates": "",
  "Only proteins": "",
  "Fats, proteins, and carbohydrates, since the pancreas produces lipase, proteases, and amylase": "",
  "Pancreatic exocrine insufficiency in cystic fibrosis blocks the delivery of lipase (fat digestion), trypsin/chymotrypsin (protein digestion), amylase (starch digestion), and nucleases to the duodenum, resulting in maldigestion of all macronutrients, most notably fats.": "",
  "A physician asks a student to explain why acidic chyme entering the duodenum does not damage the intestinal lining. The student correctly explains that which hormone triggers the release of a protective substance?": "",
  "Secretin stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion to neutralize the acidic chyme": "",
  "Gastrin triggers mucus secretion in the duodenum": "",
  "CCK triggers bile release to neutralize acid": "",
  "GIP stimulates acid production in the stomach to prevent excess chyme release": "",
  "When acidic chyme enters the duodenum, S-cells release secretin, which stimulates the pancreatic duct cells to secrete bicarbonate-rich fluid. This bicarbonate neutralizes the acid, raising the pH to the near-neutral range needed for intestinal enzymes to function and protecting the duodenal mucosa.": ""
}